Title: 20" 3 Speed Cleary Owl Kids Bikes
text: We have 2- 20" Cleary Owl Kids bikes for sale. One is pink and the other is blue.  Both have been upgraded to the internally geared Sturmey Archer 3 speed hub. Each bike also has upgraded mountain bike pedals and mountain bike tires. We will include the single speed wheels, street tires and original pedals with the purchase. These bikes are designed for kids ages 5-7 with an inseam measurement of 19-23". Both bikes were purchased locally from Revolution Bicycles at the end of 2020. We are asking $225 a piece or $400 for both bikes.

Title: Custom Callen Camper
text: Just recently got a custom callen camper built for my long bed 95 dodge ram 2500.  Jim Callen is incredibly difficult to get a hold of recently but has been making campers since the 1970's.  They are legendary campers, known for their durability with a full welded steel frame and lightweight aluminum skin.  Jim is retired now but is making them at his home shop, although talking with him about rising material prices during the build process it seems to be getting too expensive for him to continue making them.     This is like a camper shell and bolts on the the bed rails allowing you to maintain your bed space and easily store things like longboards, dirt bikes or atvs.  I got mine with a maxxair fan and led dome lighting that currently is just set up to run off the battery.   Was going to build an auxiliary battery system but have decided to sell.    Picked up the camper in november and built the simple bed/kitchen set up for a month long trip to baja.  It was super comfortable down there even through the wind and rain.  I loved having it but have realized that I will need something a little more low profile for the forest roads that I work on in the fall and don't want to have to take the shell on and off.  I'm not in a super rush to sell it but will entertain reasonable offers. Also will take a smaller aluminum shell as partial trade.

Title: 1985 Trek 620 Touring
text: Up for sale is a 1985 Trek 620. in very good condition, some light scratches on top tube and chainstay, and the decals aren't perfect.  Otherwise, the dark blue metallic paint is beautiful. While the construction and geometry of the frame and fork are considered by many to be quite ideal for loaded touring, even better than the top of the line 720 thanks to its super long chainstays, some of the parts it originally came with (I'm referring to the Helicomatic hub and the Huret Eco Duopar rear derailer) were less up to the task. So, these are the "new" parts I replaced them and other components with, in most cases trying my best to stay within the correct time period, except when a more modern version offered a clear upgrade in performance: - Shimano Deore rear derailer - NOS Shimano 36 h Deore XT front and rear hubs, laced to 27" Sun Ringle rims with Dt Swiss 14g spokes.  This rear hub is quite special: it has a solid axle, and originally came with a 6 speed freehub body, meaning it accepts a cassette instead of a freewheel, and because of the bearing placement it is almost impossible to break the axle. I replaced it with a 7 speed freehub body because 7 speed cassettes are much more common. - Dia Compe bar end shifters and down tube cable stops - Nitto Randoneur handlebars - Nitto lugged stem - Tiagra brake levers (admittedly these are not even close to being period correct but I feel that aero levers offer better braking than the non aero type) - SRAM 7 speed cassette and chain (again, totally modern but in my opinion worth the upgrade in shift quality) - Velo Orange aluminum fenders and leather flaps.  I am especially happy with the way these fenders look and perform on this bike.  They are light, quiet, and provide full coverage protection for the rider and the frame. - all new cables, housing, chain and grease. - Panaracer 27 1-3/8" "Super Hard" tires.  I kept (but cleaned and repacked with Phil Wood grease) the buttery smooth Shimano bottom bracket and super durable Stronglight A9 headset. While those were out, I treated the insides of the frame and fork with Boeshield T9.  The crankset is the original Shimano 600, which I took completely apart and cleaned before reassembling and the brakes are the original Shimano XT cantilevers.  Original Huret Pilot front derailer and Sugino seatpost round it all out.  The bike is a joy to ride, after assembling it I rode it to work a few times.  I live at the top of Humboldt Hill and it was a blast riding down it.  Up, is another story (let's just say I was very happy to have that 28 tooth granny gear).  I probably put about 200 miles on it.  I am about 6'1 and this frame fits me well.  Included with the bike but not pictured are the original and matching Blackburn rear rack, and all the original components.  Since I don't have a "parts bin" I had to purchase all the parts I installed so I was able to keep a tally which all in all (frame and parts no labour) added up to about $1400.    If you have read this far, and are interested, please contact me at 7O7-two-nine-eight-98-fourOh.

Title: Dahon Mu8 folding bike, 8 speed
text: Used regularly for the first 4 or 5 years of its life, regular servicing at Adventure's Edge, but has been sitting idle for a while. Title: Clamp-on Downtube Shifter Adapter
text: This is a clamp-on down tube shifter adapter for vintage road bikes without braze-on shifter mounts.   This adapter will allow the use of most standard friction or indexing downtube shifters. Way more quality options available compared to clamp-on or stem mount shifters.   Purchased from an eBay seller (paddythepeddler) who makes these with very high quality hose clamps and a laser welder. Super solid and well made.  This adapter is specifically sized for road frames with a 28.6mm downtube diameter but will fit 27-29mm diameter tubes.   Worked great but I don't need it anymore. They currently sell for about $65.00.

Title: HYBRID BIKE - TREK Multitrack 720, 20" frame, like new......make offer

It will fit someone from about 5'3" to 5'10", give or take a little.  Some riders like a larger frame, some like a smaller one.  It has new tubes, new tires, new chain, new brakes, new stem. I just can't get my leg up and over this bike.  If I can ride again I'll have to get a step over or step thru model.
